This command is used to connect to a remote server using SSH (Secure Shell) and forward a local port to the remote server. The `-i` option specifies the identity file, which in this case is `~/UserKey.pem`. The `-C` option enables compression of the data being transmitted, and the `-L` option specifies that you want to forward the local port 25900 to the remote server's port 5900. Finally, the `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com` specifies the username and hostname of the remote server you want to connect to.

In this case, the command is used to connect to an Amazon EC2 instance using SSH and forwarding a local port to the remote server's port 5900, which is typically used for VNC connections. The `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com` part specifies the username and hostname of the remote server you want to connect to.

It's important to note that this command assumes that you have already generated an SSH key pair and added the public key to the `authorized_keys` file on the remote server, and that you are using the private key in the identity file specified by the `-i` option.
